l exegesis characteristic of the Middle Ages and Renaissance. Specific subjects include the centrality of the psalms and the image of David to European poets, therelation of pagan myth to biblical truth, the complexity and purposefulness of Camoes's intertextual strategies, the underappreciated influence on Camões of Juan Boscán, the exegetical control of the poem's elaborate numerological schemes, and the concept of palinode as literary genre and personal moral statement. John V. Fleming is the Louis W. Fairchild Professor of English and Professor of Comparative Literature emeritus at Princeton University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aBible.  aEnglish.  aallegory.  acatholicism.  achristianity.  agenre.  ahistory.  aliterary strategies.  aliterature.  amanusript.  amedieval literature.  amiddle ages.  apoetry.  areligion.  areligious studies.  arenaissance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440210423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440210/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles